Title:
Tutorial example  - high harmonics for H-atom in two-color field

Use fundamental and perpendicular 2nd harmonic


# you may check the "Laser" file in each run directory for the actual field

Definitions:
Rscal   = complex scaling radius and surfac pickup radius
Lambda = longer wave length (nm)
Phase  = Phase offset of the shorter wave length component

#define Rscal 20.
#define Lambda 800
#define Phase pi/4

# acceleation form is far the best, velocity and length included for demonstration purposes only
# if   compiled with -D_FFTW_ fourierer transforms will be written to "harmonics"
# else the values will be in "dipoles" with an equidistant time grid
Dipole: acceleration,velocity,length

# NOTE: for acceleration we need to use the derivative of the actual radial potential, this
#  is taken care of for some potentials by the class Harmonics, where also the above input is defined



# CAUTION: carefully tuned minimal basis for given parameters
#          carefully verify convergence for actual use
Axis: name,nCoefficients,lower end, upper end,functions,order
 Phi,9
 Eta,15,-1,1, assocLegendre{Phi}
 Rn,25, 0.,Rscal,polynomial,25
 Rn,20, Rscal,Infty,polExp[0.7]


Absorption: kind, axis, theta, upper
ECS,Rn,0.5,Rscal

# for harmonics, there is no reason to truncate the potential
# -> disabled
# Operator: truncate=20,smooth=15

Operator: hamiltonian='1/2<<Laplacian>>-<<Coulomb>>'
Operator: interaction='iLaserAz[t]<<D/DZ>>+iLaserAx[t]<<D/DX>>'

# the p[0,20] before : defines a name instead of the default "ExpN"
Operator: expectationValue='p[0,20]:<1><1><chi[0,20]>'


# play with different relative phases here
Laser: shape, I(W/cm2), FWHM, lambda(nm), polarAngle,phiCEO
cos8,  2.e14,  8. OptCyc, Lambda,   0.
cos8, 0.25e14, 8. OptCyc, Lambda/2,90.,Phase

TimePropagation: print,store,cutEnergy,accuracy,operatorThreshold
0.125 OptCyc,0.05 au,50,1.e-7,1.e-6

